{
    "ocr_text": "Mr. Hans Fehlinger,
Lachner St. 4a,
Munich, Germany.

Dear Sir:

Your favor of the 7th instant has been duly received and contents noted.

Secretary Morrison has already written you, and sent you International Money Order for $5.00, so it is unnecessary to make any further reference except to express my regret for the delay.

You say you have not received the March issue of the AMERICAN FEDERATIONIST, and, therefore, I am sending you another copy under separate cover, and I trust that it will reach you promptly.

I imagine that by this time you have received the Constitution of the International Union of Horse Shoers and their monthly magazine as well as the publications of the American Academy of Political and Social Science. At the time I wrote you in regard to them I also wrote to their headquarters requesting that the matters be forwarded to you. However, if you have not received them by the time this letter reaches you please advise me and I will take this matter up further.

You will please accept my thanks for the copy of the "Socialistische Monatshefte" which you sent me.

April 25, 1910.",
    "summary": "The letter dated April 25, 1910, addressed to Mr. Hans Fehlinger acknowledges receipt of his earlier communication. It mentions a previous correspondence by Secretary Morrison, who sent an International Money Order. The sender is addressing the issue of the missing March issue of the AMERICAN FEDERATIONIST by sending another copy. The letter also mentions the potential receipt of other publications and requests further notification if matters are not resolved.",
